Driver, who has been leading the Trust for more than nine years, said she was thrilled that Cooper would be taking over from her as they worked together over the past six years. “I am fully confident that she is extremely capable of fulfilling the responsibilities of this role and continue to grow and strengthen the trust going forward,” she said. Cooper holds an Honours degree in political science and public administration through Nelson Mandela Metropolitan University and has more than 24 years of fundraising and development experience. She has worked as a director at Rape Crisis Cape Town Trust and St Joseph’s Home for Chronically Ill Children. Before being appointed chief executive of the Children’s Hospital Trust, Cooper was the head of fundraising for the same trust. Cooper is a passionate advocate of rights for women and children. She believes in the value of teamwork and said she was fortunate to lead exceptional teams in her organisations. Cape Argus